Subject:     FORMATION OF MCDONNELL DOUGLAS MANUFACTURING AND 
             ENGINEERING SYSTEMS COMPANY



After carefully considering the recommendations of the Strategic 
Task Force on Discrete Manufacturing, the ISG Executive Board has 
decided to form the McDonnell Douglas Manufacturing and Engineering 
Systems Company.

The company's mission will be to give the ISG worldwide penetration 
of the manufacturing and the architectural, engineering and 
construction markets by developing and marketing a strong line of 
graphics-based products to those markets.

McDonnell Douglas Manufacturing and Engineering Systems Company 
will have an objective of generating 1990 revenues of $1.3 billion, 
and after-tax profits of $100 million (in 1983 dollars).

In pursuit of those goals, the company's initial strategy will be:

  1)  To exploit the ISG's strong position in CAD/CAM and to focus 
      our efforts in the Computer-Integrated Manufacturing (CIM) 
      products field.

  2)  To emphasize development and marketing of Computer-Aided 
      Engineering (CAE) products.

  3)  To realize the technology-sharing and marketing advantages of 
      a combined CAE and CAD/CAM thrust.

The Executive Board does not plan to proceed, at least for the 
present, with applications in manufacturing resource planning and 
in automated material handling which were recommended by the Task 
Force.  Instead, the management of McDonnell Douglas Manufacturing 
and Engineering Systems Company will review the Task Force 
recommendations and propose what additional areas of endeavor they 
believe will be necessary to make the company a strong, long-term 
competitor in the fields of CIM and CAE.






The McDonnell Douglas Manufacturing and Engineering Systems Company 
will be headquartered in St. Louis.  It will operate as two 
business units--the Manufacturing Industry Systems Company and the 
Architectural, Engineering and Construction Information Systems 
Company.  The latter business unit will include the newly acquired 
Applied Research of Cambridge, Ltd.

The new company will be headed by John Clancy, who is promoted to 
President - McDonnell Douglas Manufacturing and Engineering Systems 
Company.  He will report to the ISG Executive Board through 
Bob Fischer.  George Meister continues as Senior Vice President and 
General Manager - McDonnell Douglas Manufacturing Industry Systems 
Company.  Paul Scholten is promoted to Vice President - Strategic 
Planning and Technology for the McDonnell Douglas Manufacturing and 
Engineering Systems Company. Further appointments will be announced 
later.

John Clancy will head a team to develop a business plan and a plan 
to fill out the company's organizational structure.  The company is 
expected to be in operation effective 1 July 1985.



