Subject:  MANAGEMENT  AND  PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENT PHASES - 1986
          POLICY   CHANGES   ON   TRAVEL  EXPENSES,  TUITION  AND
          CANCELLATION



The  Management  and Professional Development organization (M&PD)
has  scheduled  a  full  complement  of  Phase  programs in 1986.
These  residential  Phases will again be held in St. Louis at the
Doubletree    Hotel   and   Conference   Center   (Formerly   the
Breckenridge).

In  1984  and  1985,  the Phase program costs were not charged to
the  attendees department or business unit.  The only direct cost
was  travel  to  St.  Louis  for  out-of-town attendees.  Several
policy  changes  have  been  adopted by ISG Senior Management for
1986.

In summary they include the following:

    -  A  $500  tuition fee will be paid for each Phase attendee.
       (This  charge  will  be  distributed  within each business
       unit according to that unit's policy.)

    -  Each  business  unit has committed to a specific number of
       attendees  to  each  Phase.    Participant space that goes
       unfilled   through:     unscheduled  attendees,  scheduled
       attendee  cancellation,  or  no  shows  will incur a $1500
       charge  to  the  appropriate  business  unit or attendee's
       department.

    -  The  allowable  travel expenses associated with attendance
       at the Phase will be charged to M&PD.

Allowable  travel  expenses  chargeable  to M&PD include lodging,
all  meals,  lowest  available  air  fare  and  other  incidental
expenses  such  as  mileage  to  and  from  the  airport, airport
parking  and  baggage  fees.    It  will not include rental cars,
additional days per diem or higher fare airline routing.

To   accommodate  the  flexibility  to  schedule  extra  days  in
St.  Louis  or  other  itinerary changes for appropriate business
purposes,  the  attendees'  TR's  and Travel Expense reports will
still  be  issued  and  approved  by  the  appropriate department
manager.    The  traveler will receive with his airline ticket an
invoice  copy  showing  the  allowable  air  fare  and actual air
fare.  (Allowable and actual air fare will be the same if the



